From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: equip-1 <equip1@local>
Date: Mon, 30 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] btusb: Add AICSEMI AIC8800D80 with broken extended LE quirks

The AIC8800D80 USB WiFi+BT combo chip (a69c:8d81) exposes a standard
Bluetooth class interface (0xe0/0x01/0x01) and reports HCI/LMP version 5.4
with HCI_LE_EXT_ADV set in its LE supported features.  BlueZ therefore issues
extended LE advertising and scanning HCI commands.

However, the chip firmware does not properly implement these BT5 extended
commands.  The following errors appear in kernel logs:
  Bluetooth: hci0: Opcode 0x2036 failed: -16  (LE_Set_Extended_Scan_Parameters)
  Bluetooth: hci0: Opcode 0x2042 failed: -16  (LE_Set_Extended_Scan_Enable)
  Bluetooth: hci0: Unable to disable scanning: -16

Testing confirms that legacy LE commands (LE_Set_Advertising_Parameters/Data/
Enable, LE_Set_Scan_Parameters/Enable) work correctly.

Add AIC8800D80 to btusb_table[] before the generic class entry.  A dedicated
setup function (btusb_setup_aic8800) sets HCI_QUIRK_BROKEN_EXT_SCAN so BlueZ
uses legacy LE scan commands.

Tested on Radxa Rock 2F (RK3528) with AIC8800D80, Linux 6.18.24-yocto.

Signed-off-by: equip-1 <equip1@local>
---
 drivers/bluetooth/btusb.c | 33 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 33 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/bluetooth/btusb.c b/drivers/bluetooth/btusb.c
index 1111111..2222222 100644
--- a/drivers/bluetooth/btusb.c
+++ b/drivers/bluetooth/btusb.c
@@ -66,6 +66,7 @@
 #define BTUSB_INTEL_NO_WBS_SUPPORT	BIT(26)
 #define BTUSB_ACTIONS_SEMI		BIT(27)
+#define BTUSB_AIC8800			BIT(28)

 static const struct usb_device_id btusb_table[] = {
 	/* Generic Bluetooth USB device */
@@ -70,6 +71,14 @@
 	/* Generic Bluetooth USB device */
 	{ USB_DEVICE_INFO(0xe0, 0x01, 0x01) },

+	/*
+	 * AICSEMI AIC8800D80 USB WiFi+BT combo (a69c:8d81).
+	 * Reports BT 5.4 but extended LE advertising and scanning HCI commands
+	 * fail with -EBUSY.  Legacy LE commands work correctly.
+	 * Must appear before the generic USB_DEVICE_INFO(0xe0,0x01,0x01) entry.
+	 */
+	{ USB_DEVICE(0xa69c, 0x8d81), .driver_info = BTUSB_AIC8800 },
+
 	/* Generic Bluetooth AMP device */
 	{ USB_DEVICE_INFO(0xe0, 0x01, 0x04), .driver_info = BTUSB_AMP },

@@ -3717,6 +3725,20 @@
 }

 static DEVICE_ATTR_RW(isoc_alt);
+
+static int btusb_setup_aic8800(struct hci_dev *hdev)
+{
+	/*
+	 * AIC8800D80: the chip firmware reports BT 5.4 capability but does not
+	 * implement extended LE scan/adv HCI commands correctly.  Set the
+	 * broken-ext-scan quirk so the kernel BlueZ stack uses legacy
+ 	 * LE_Set_Scan_Parameters / LE_Set_Scan_Enable commands instead.
+	 *
+	 * Legacy LE advertising is handled in userspace via raw HCI commands
+	 * (see companion-net hciadv.go) pending a kernel-level broken-ext-adv
+	 * quirk being added to include/net/bluetooth/hci.h.
+	 */
+	set_bit(HCI_QUIRK_BROKEN_EXT_SCAN, &hdev->quirks);
+	return 0;
+}

 static int btusb_probe(struct usb_interface *intf,
 		       const struct usb_device_id *id)
@@ -4010,6 +4032,11 @@
 	if (id->driver_info & BTUSB_ACTIONS_SEMI) {
 		/* Support is advertised, but not implemented */
 		set_bit(HCI_QUIRK_BROKEN_ERR_DATA_REPORTING, &hdev->quirks);
@@ -4020,6 +4042,11 @@
 		set_bit(HCI_QUIRK_BROKEN_WRITE_AUTH_PAYLOAD_TIMEOUT, &hdev->quirks);
 	}

+	if (id->driver_info & BTUSB_AIC8800)
+		hdev->setup = btusb_setup_aic8800;
+
 	if (!reset)
 		set_bit(HCI_QUIRK_RESET_ON_CLOSE, &hdev->quirks);

